Reading a topic at the Gamua Forum, it turned out that setting the color of a quad was very costly ( up to 30% of the performance for one project there)

http://forum.starling-framework.org/topic/speed-up-quadbatchaddquad

After doing some digging, I came up with these possible additions to the Quad and VertexData classes:

For Quad:

```
    public function setColorChannels(r:Number, g:Number, b:Number) : void
    {
        for (var i:int=0; i<4; ++i)
             mVertexData.setColorChannels(i, r, g, b);

        onVertexDataChanged();

        if ( r < 1 || g < 1 || b < 1 )
            mTinted = true;
        else if ( alpha != 1.0) 
            mTinted = true;
        else mTinted = mVertexData.tinted;
    }
```

and for VertexData:

```
    public function setColorChannels(vertexID:int, r:Number, g:Number, b:Number):void
    {
        var offset:int = vertexID * ELEMENTS_PER_VERTEX + COLOR_OFFSET;
        if ( mPremultipliedAlpha )
        {
            var multiplier:Number = mRawData[offset + 3];

            mRawData[offset  ] = r * multiplier;
            mRawData[offset+1] = g * multiplier;
            mRawData[offset+2] = b * multiplier;
        }
        else
        {
            mRawData[offset  ] = r ;
            mRawData[offset+1] = g;
            mRawData[offset+2] = b;
        }
    }
```

Running through a quad 50000 times and setting:

q.color = 0xFF0000;

takes about 40% more time than doing:

q.setColorChannels(1.0, 0.0, 0.0);

on my stationary PC (approx 14-15 ms vs 8-9 ms )

I don't know if this is something to consider, but it is a suggested performance boost that might be beneficial. Or it might just clutter up the API, what do I know. :)

Let me know what you think.

Also, a general tip if is to check 
if ( q.color != desiredColor )

before calling q.color = desiredColor;

